Such errors were caused by the informa- tion coming at second or third hand to the writer. He tells us, however, much that is altogether new and which we can acquire from no other source. The most valuable chapters in the earlier part of the Life are those which relate to the building or renovation of the churches of Ripon, Hexham, and York‚ places with which Eddi must have been thoroughly familiar. There is less indeed about York than some would expect to find, but we must remember that Hexham was of Wilfrid’s own creating‚ and that to Ripon he was most devotedly attached.
